<subSubSection pageId="103" pageNumber="104" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="103.[189,1398,1107,1208]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
Although 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman" box="[310,615,1107,1134]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref265860" refString="Hayman R. W., Misonne X. &amp; Verheyen W. N. 1966. The bats of the Congo and of Rwanda and Burundi. Annalen van het Koninklijk Museum voor Midden Afrika, Zoologische Wetenschappen, Ser. 8, 154: 1 - 105." type="journal article" year="1966">
Hayman 
<emphasis box="[419,480,1107,1133]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">et al.</emphasis>
(1966: 56)
</bibRefCitation>
considered 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hindei Thomas" authorityYear="1901" box="[762,879,1108,1134]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Scotoecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[762,879,1108,1134]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Scotoecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rafinesque" authorityYear="1819" box="[1135,1257,1108,1133]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nycticeius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1135,1257,1108,1133]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Nycticeius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, its generic status was already restored by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rosevear" box="[553,809,1144,1171]" firstAuthor="Rosevear" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refId="ref272471" refString="Rosevear D. R. 1965. The Bats of West Africa. Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London." type="book" year="1965">Rosevear (1965: 246)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Koopman" box="[868,1119,1144,1171]" firstAuthor="Koopman" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref268567" refString="Koopman K. F. 1965. Status of forms described or recorded by J. A. Allen in the &quot; American Museum Congo Expedition of Bats &quot;. American Museum Novitates 2219: 1 - 34. Available from http: // hdl. handle. net / 2246 / 4012 [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1965">Koopman (1965: 17)</bibRefCitation>
, who were followed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hill" box="[189,396,1181,1208]" firstAuthor="Hill" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="167 - 188" refId="ref266287" refString="Hill J. E. 1974 b. A review of Scotoecus Thomas, 1901 (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology 27 (4): 167 - 188." type="journal article" year="1974" yearSuffix="b">Hill (1974b: 171)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Koopman" box="[409,663,1181,1208]" firstAuthor="Koopman" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="137 - 241" refId="ref268797" refString="Koopman K. F. 1993. Order Chiroptera. In: Wilson D. E. &amp; Reeder D. M. (eds) Mammal Species of the World: a Taxonomic and Geographic Reference. Second edition: 137 - 241. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, D. C. and London." type="book chapter" year="1993">Koopman (1993: 226</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Koopman" box="[675,794,1182,1208]" firstAuthor="Koopman" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="60" refId="ref268855" refString="Koopman K. F. 1994. Chiroptera: Systematics. In: Niethammer J., Schliemann H. &amp; Starck D. (eds) Handbook of Zoology 8 (Mammalia) (60). W. De Gruyter, Berlin and New York." type="book chapter" year="1994">1994: 127</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Simmons" box="[860,1109,1181,1208]" firstAuthor="Simmons" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="312 - 567" refId="ref273235" refString="Simmons N. B. 2005. Order Chiroptera. In: Wilson D. E. &amp; Reeder D. M. (eds) Mammal Species of the World: A Taxonomic and Geographic Reference: 312 - 567. The John Hopkins University Press, Baltimore." type="book chapter" year="2005">Simmons (2005: 461</bibRefCitation>
, 464).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="103.[189,1398,1249,1387]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
Only one specimen of this species has been reported from the CRB area up until now: RMCA 22412 from Baudouinville (= Moba), Tanganyika Province. It was first mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman" box="[1160,1398,1286,1313]" firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="41 - 45" refId="ref265714" refString="Hayman R. W. 1957. Further notes on African Bats. Revue de zoologie et de botanique africaines 56 (1 - 2): 41 - 45." type="journal article" year="1957">Hayman (1957: 44)</bibRefCitation>
and subsequently confirmed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fain" box="[570,773,1323,1350]" firstAuthor="Fain" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="131 - 167" refId="ref261300" refString="Fain A. 1959. Les acariens psoriques parasites des chauves-souris. XI. Le genre Notoedres Railliet 1893. Revue de zoologie et de botanique africaines 60 (1 - 2): 131 - 167." type="journal article" year="1959">Fain (1959: 161)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hill" box="[788,999,1323,1349]" firstAuthor="Hill" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="167 - 188" refId="ref266287" refString="Hill J. E. 1974 b. A review of Scotoecus Thomas, 1901 (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology 27 (4): 167 - 188." type="journal article" year="1974" yearSuffix="b">Hill (1974b: 177)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Anciaux de Faveaux" box="[1012,1393,1323,1350]" firstAuthor="Anciaux de Faveaux" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refId="ref256260" refString="Anciaux de Faveaux M. 1983. Les cycles annuels de reproduction chez les chiropteres phytophiles au Shaba (SE Zaire) et au Rwanda. In: Van der Straeten E., Verheyen W. N. &amp; De Vree F. (eds) Proceedings of the Third International Colloquim on Ecology and Taxonomy of African Small Mammals. Antwerpen," type="book" year="1983">Anciaux de Faveaux (1983: 29)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Monadjem" box="[189,542,1360,1387]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Monadjem" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refId="ref270370" refString="Monadjem A., Taylor P., Cotterill F. P. D. &amp; Schoeman M. C. 2010 b. Bats of Southern and Central Africa. A biogeographic and Taxonomic Synthesis. Wits University Press, Johannesburg." type="book" year="2010" yearSuffix="b">
Monadjem 
<emphasis box="[323,382,1360,1386]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">et al.</emphasis>
(2010b: 506)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[599,779,1360,1386]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refId="ref264870" refString="Happold M. &amp; Happold D. 2013. Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats. Bloomsbury, London." type="book" year="2013">Happold (2013</bibRefCitation>
aj: 668).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="103.[189,1399,1428,1826]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
The distribution map presented by 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[601,781,1428,1454]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refId="ref264870" refString="Happold M. &amp; Happold D. 2013. Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats. Bloomsbury, London." type="book" year="2013">Happold (2013</bibRefCitation>
aj: 668) clearly illustrates the rarity of this species in scientific collections, as only individual records are plotted, with the exception of small areas in 
<collectingCountry name="Sierra Leone" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Sierra Leone</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[316,465,1502,1528]" name="Gambia" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">The Gambia</collectingCountry>
. The species occurs from the latter country in West Africa to Northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1276,1398,1502,1528]" name="Cameroon" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
and then continuing from northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[655,749,1539,1565]" name="Uganda" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Uganda</collectingCountry>
, over 
<collectingCountry box="[821,930,1539,1565]" name="Tanzania" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1095,1155,1539,1565]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">DRC</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1213,1368,1539,1565]" name="Mozambique" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
to the 
<collectingCountry box="[234,295,1576,1602]" name="South Africa" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">RSA</collectingCountry>
. This leaves a wide gap between 
<collectingCountry box="[700,822,1576,1602]" name="Cameroon" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[883,978,1576,1602]" name="Uganda" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Uganda</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="ACR" box="[989,1213,1576,1602]" firstAuthor="ACR" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refId="ref254905" refString="ACR. 2016. African Chiroptera Report. AfricanBats, Pretoria. Available from http: // www. africanbats. org / index. php / publications / africa-chiroptera-report [accessed 28 Sep. 2017]." type="url" year="2016">ACR (2016: 1283)</bibRefCitation>
mentions three specimens from the 
<collectingCountry box="[429,729,1613,1639]" name="Central African Republic" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Central African Republic</collectingCountry>
, which narrow this gap a bit, but it nevertheless remains wide. We concur with Ansell &amp; Dowsett (1988: 43), who state that “this species is rarely collected, though it has a wide range from 
<collectingCountry box="[580,673,1688,1714]" name="Senegal" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Senegal</collectingCountry>
to southern 
<collectingCountry box="[824,983,1688,1714]" name="Mozambique" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
. It is no doubt more widespread in 
<collectingCountry box="[189,279,1725,1751]" name="Malawi" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Malawi</collectingCountry>
than the single recorded locality would indicate”, and believe this is also the case for many other countries. The SDM map suggests that 
<taxonomicName box="[651,806,1762,1788]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nycticeius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="albofuscus">
<emphasis box="[651,806,1762,1788]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">S. albofuscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
potentially can occur along the northern border of the 
<collectingCountry box="[232,295,1799,1825]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">DRC</collectingCountry>
, where it can bridge the gap between the two areas where it has been found up until now.
</paragraph>
